<font color="#FF0000">WELCOME BACK, KOTTER</font><br>
<tt>Sun Aug 17  8:52:46 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Gerald,<br><br>
It is good to have you back. I am always glad to hear your well informed opinion, and am reassured by your words that you present a solid and objective presentation of the Vietnam War when you speak to students. It is fitting to say that you deserved the Bronze Star, and that it is paying dividends because of your work in schools.<br><br>
Like you, I have always been hesitant to allow myself to think that I was deserving of any medals I received. A funny thing is that the two medals of which I am most proud are the National Defense Ribbon and The Vietnam Service Medal.<br><br>
I was with two other men in Quang Ngai City, driving them in a jeep. I had been reassigned to my &quot;job in the rear&quot;. There was an explosion nearby - its source we couldn't determine. One of the men - a medic - immediately jumped out and ran over to where a group of people had gathered around a little boy who was badly wounded. My Lieutenant told me to *drive* to where the little boy and our medic were. As an infantryman it was against my better judgment, as I thought it possible we may be driving through a minefield.<br><br>
I will always feel that what we did that day reflected the good that Americans were capable of doing. Did we receive a medal? Nah. But in my heart dwells the satisfaction of knowing what a group of Vietnamese witnessed three Americans doing.<br><br>
A vet saying that the war was a mistake is not without risk. Oftentimes this opinion is branded as being disloyal. More power to those who stand up to those who attempt to intimidate. Right on, perfesser.<br><br>

<p><code>-- .wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


